  "text": "As was observed previously with the MZ virus [CITATION_1] , the highest viral loads were recorded at 2 and 3 days p.i. At these two time points, viral loads in the lungs were significantly higher in NSdel8084-inoculated chickens (Fig.  3a , two-tailed P50.015 for the grouped day 2+3 values), whereas viral loads at later time points (days 4 and 7 p.i.) were similar between the two viruses. Thus, replication of the MZ WT virus in the lungs seemed to be delayed compared with that of NSdel8084. In the upper respiratory tract, vRNA could be quantified in the oropharyngeal swabs from days 1 to 4 p.i. From days 2 to 4, only two of 12 of the oropharyngeal swabs were positive in WT-inoculated animals compared with eight of 12 in the NSdel8084-inoculated chickens (Fig. 3c ). Viral loads in the kidney likely reflected viral systemic transport, and we observed a strong correlation between the viral loads in the respiratory tract and kidney : between days 2 and 4, vRNA was quantified in the kidney of only two out of 12 WT-inoculated chickens and in nine out of 12 NSdel8084-inoculated birds ( Fig. 3b, d ). Overall, four animals in the WT-infected group were virus-negative in all tested tissues (two at day 2, one at day 3 and one at day 7) as compared with only one virusnegative bird (at day 4) in the NSdel8084-inoculated group. Among the WT-inoculated birds, the two kidney-positive birds at day 4 were those with both the highest viral load in the respiratory tract ( Fig. 3d ) and highest lesion score in the lung. Finally, no vRNA was detected in the brains, which were collected at days 3 and 4 (data not shown).",
